    \section*{Infinite Sets}
    Some sets have infinitely many elements, which can be indicated by an ellipsis ``$\dots$". For example, the natural numbers,
    \begin{equation*}
        \mathbb{N} = \set{1, 2, 3, \dots}
    \end{equation*}
    
    \begin{definition}
    A \textbf{finite} set has a finite number of elements, i.e. the number of elements in the set is a whole number. An \textbf{infinite} set has infinitely many elements, i.e. the number of elements in the set is not a whole number.
    \end{definition}
    
    \section*{Venn Diagrams, Euler Diagrams}
    Relationships between sets can be represented graphically using a Venn diagram, or a Euler diagram.
    
    \section*{Applications of Venn Diagrams}
    \begin{theorem}[Addition Rule for Counting]
    \begin{equation*}
        n(A \cup B) = n(A) + n(B) - n(A \cap B)
    \end{equation*}
    \end{theorem}
    
    \section*{Aside on Sets and Math Definitions}
    Most mathematical objects are ``formally" defined in terms of sets. For example, functions are defined as a particular kind of set. In fact, numbers, such as the natural numbers, can be defined using sets. -->

    
